{"title": "Everybody Owns a Ford", "content": "...Or a Chevy. Or a Chrysler. Or a whatever... Apparently no other automobile manufacturer exists.\n\nIn many shows, all the automobiles visible on screen (or at least in the foreground) are provided by a single manufacturer, usually as a Product Placement deal. In exchange for such a lucrative freebie, the manufacturer usually demands that no competing vehicles appear in the program, and the producers happily comply. Sometimes negotiations are made for additional money if there is an added shot of the logo, key terms mentioned in dialogue or especially boasting of its performance.\n\nIn addition, all characters own brand new late model cars, no matter their income level.\n\nThis can also apply to other reasonably-expensive household items; personal computers, for instance.\n\nNote that owning a Ford is not a bad thing per se, unless it's a Pinto...\n\nSee Damage-Proof Vehicle for another trope associated with Product Placement deals with car manufacturers. For a similar trope for computers, more often paid for in kind than in cash, we observe that Everyone Owns A Mac. For when a car (or similar forms of product placement) is destroyed, see Destroy the Product Placement.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EverybodyOwnsAFord", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/RogerEbert", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/MarvelCinematicUniverse", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IronMan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheAvengers2012", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/CaptainAmericaTheWinterSoldier", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheCatInTheHat", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DemolitionMan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DrowningMona", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IRobot", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ItsAMadMadMadMadWorld", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/JamesBond", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DieAnotherDay", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/JamesBond", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/CasinoRoyale2006", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Goldfinger", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LiveAndLetD